Mercury Cafe Swing Band Study.
 
When plein air painting while everyone is moving around so much singing and dancing, I feel content with simply capturing the general feel or impression rather than painting the exact details.
A little painting this afternoon on the winter solstice. I was really getting into the blues and purples of the snow in the shadows.
Whether you call them Christmas lights or winter lights, they sure make the season brighter and the nights more cheery! 😊

Happy new year! Here’s my last painting of 2022, a gouache painting in my sketchbook over a green casein primer just for fun, painted in my living room. For the painting I used a secondary color palette: Orange, green and purple, plus white. The scene is a view from the intersection of St. Urbain and Laurent in Montreal, from a photo I took about a week and a half ago on December 23.

My New Year’s Eve was fun and low key with my partner Tara, mostly spent inside making art before we reigned in 2023 with a hike up on Mt. Sanitas overlooking Boulder. We were the only ones up on our spot on the mountain, apart from two mule deer that were 50 feet uphill from us (see if you can spot them in one of my pictures). At midnight we could hear people cheering and making noise in town, and saw a few fireworks off in the distance.

For 2023, keep an eye out for big things coming from me. Plenty of new videos are in the works, and hopefully more YouTube stuff. I have a heavy travel schedule lined up, so keep an eye out for paintings from various places around the US, Europe, Australia and Japan. I will be releasing postcards on my website soon, and possibly even a book later on in the year. Maybe a few murals as well.

A painting of the house from “A Christmas Story”, featuring a palette consisting of Titanium white, Indian yellow Deep, medium portrait pink, caput mortuum violet, dioxazine purple, Perylene Black, cobalt turquoise and azo yellow green.

Two paintings of the flatirons from today. Which one do you like better? Both were done in oil paint, the first one was painted with titanium white, yellow ochre and ivory black… the second one with titanium white, yellow ochre, mars red and pthalo turquoise.

Birthday tribute to ‘Billy’ Eduard Albert Meier (born February 3, 1937). Last year, Billy gave me written permission to make paintings of his beamship photos (which are by the way not UFOs, since they are identified, they have been seen by many people in his area, and we have a lot of information about them — so they are IFOs!).

Street scene in my hometown of Chagrin Falls, Ohio. Painted the day before Thanksgiving on November 23, 2022. 🦃 The building I put highlights on in the very center of the painting is where my dad’s office was located back in the late ‘80s - early ‘90s. He was an architect, and his spot was on the second floor, corner office. That’s one place where I made a lot of art as a kid and learned a lot. #pleinair #pleinairpainting #chagrinfalls #chagrinfallsohio

Ultra mini oil painting of the Flatirons in Boulder, CO, painted with only Titanium White and two colors – Burnt Sienna and Indigo. This painting is on a wood panel in an Altoids Smalls container, and the painting itself is only 1 x 1.75 inches.
Winter plein air painting in Montreal, painting over a cool turquoise undertone. Are you excited for spring, or would you rather have winter stick around for longer?

It was fun because of the unusual color palette: bismuth yellow, ruby madder alizarin and cobalt turquoise light, plus white. “East Boulder Evening Light in Early Autumn (Limited Palette)” #pleinair #pleinairpainting #bouldercolorado #oilpainting #mini #miniature #miniaturepainting #minipainting #tinypainting #tinyart #pocketsize #colorado #coloradoart #coloradoartist

Here’s a nocturne I painted back in January, in Puerto Vallarta, Mexico. The painting looks a lot darker than the surrounding area outside, but I swear, I really did paint it exactly how it looked in real life! The slow shutter of the camera made everything look a lot brighter.

“Nocturne View of Buildings in Puerto Vallarta (Limited Palette)”

There was a spring snow dusting on the mountains and I wanted to paint it with an altered secondary color palette – cadmium yellow medium, dioxazine purple and permanent green light. It’s altered because my orange is more on the yellow side. Normally if I use a secondary palette, I use pthalo green, which makes an ok blue when mixed with dioxazine purple. But when I mixed purple with the permanent green light, it looked grey, so that’s why I opted for a purple sky. 🤷‍♂️ 

“Early Spring Snow Dusting in Boulder with Purple Sky (Limited Palette)”

The raw, primal power of nature. Two cloud paintings from the other night, and some photos I took. Which painting do you like better, # 1 or 2? ⛈️ In other news, as of yesterday morning I am now an uncle! Congratulations @margaretlyon and @vitamin_d_p 🫶💁‍♂️🤱

Hi! Here’s a black coffee at the Trident in Boulder, Colorado from several days ago. I’m not in Colorado as I’m posting this though, as I just landed in a different time zone that’s 15 hours ahead. I wonder if you can guess where I am? By the way, the palette here is titanium white, burnt sienna, sepia and cobalt blue. #pleinair #pleinairpainting #oilpainting #miniaturepainting #coffee #coffeepainting

Here’s my first painting from Japan. 🗾 I really loved this Japanese bridge in Toyama. This painting was done at sunset, but it was too dark for a photo by the time it was finished… How many koi can you spot in the koi pond? There’s also a crane hunting for fish somewhere in this picture. #pleinair #pleinairpainting #oilpainting #miniature #miniaturepainting #minipainting
Last night’s sunset over Kanazawa in oil, with a special lens flare light effect. This was fun! 🇯🇵🌇🇯🇵 (Currently posting from Osaka.)📍🗾✌️

Mini oil painting of Kofuku-Ji Temple in Nara, Japan for my 37th birthday today. 🇯🇵 This is the 8th painting I’ve done so far in Japan, and I’ve got video of it, like several of the other ones I’ve done so far. Once the trip is over I’ll post more of what I’ve done. But for now, I’m mostly staying away from editing and posting, etc., and just trying to experience Japan and not experience being glued to a screen while in Japan! 

I also rarely post in real time, so this is probably about the closest I’ll get, posting the same day. I’m not in Nara anymore though… already moved on to Kyoto. ✌️

Teddy bear latte at @micasadecoandcafeosaka in Osaka, Japan. 🐻 I drank a latte first with some Japanese fluffy pancakes, then ordered another latte for the painting. Drank that one too afterwards, even though the coffee was cold and the teddy bear all but disintegrated. I just wish I would’ve gotten the employees’ reactions on video when I showed it to them, because that was the most priceless thing ever!

Meet Ember and Wade, the main characters of @Disney and @Pixar’s new movie #Elemental, now playing only in theaters. 

When Disney invited me to make a painting for their upcoming movie “Elemental”, of course I said yes! Not only did I watch tons of Disney movies when I was a kid, but I also have a small personal connection with Disney: I first learned plein air painting in college from a teacher who was a background painter for Disney in the 90s.

What a fantastic opportunity to get to work with Disney, and what a fun painting this was to create!

Painting on a curve on a gravel road at golden hour in Bariloche, Argentina. When the light is about to go away, it’s always good to get some of those colors painted in first, because the shadows will still be there later.

I painted a cloud and a tornado formed out of the very cloud I was painting. It was a lot more prominent looking before I took this video. This is the second time a tornado has formed out of the cloud I was painting. 🌪️

The @maisonvalentino fall/winter 23/24 haute couture fashion show “Un Château” took place last Wednesday, July 5th at Chantilly Castle in France, just north of Paris. Valentino reached out and invited me to make a painting of the location of the show, and this is the result.

In the show, @pppiccioli presented a new take on couture – one where simplicity meets complexity through opulent detail. Full video of the show on Valentino’s YouTube channel.

Well, I guess I’m set on Altoids tins for a few years! Thanks so much to Eric C. for his generous donation of OVER 1000 EMPTY ALTOIDS CONTAINERS!!! He ate all these mints over the course of about 25 years – a habit which started as his method of quitting smoking. He said it was a replacement for the oral fixation part of smoking, which makes sense. Surely eating several Altoids a day is less harmful than smoking, but now as of about 6 months ago, he has kicked his Altoids addiction as well. When he found out about me and the paintings I make, he contacted me right away and wanted to know if I would use them. My answer: of course I will!

Mini painting of the Tokyo Skytree from across the Sumida River in Tokyo, Japan. 🗾

This painting will be available tomorrow (Tuesday 9/26) at 7:30pm MST, along with many others. As always, ‘link in bio’ to my website.

This was the last painting I made in Japan before heading back home back in May. This color triad is a particularly unconventional set of colors to paint with. The palette of light portrait pink, sepia and light cobalt turquoise – in that order – felt somewhat poetic like a haiku, as the choice to use them was influenced in part by the myriad of feelings that were conjured up from staying in such a foreign land. These color choices were also influenced by some of the color sensibilities I picked up on while being there.

Which one is your favorite? Some of these you have seen before and some you may be seeing for the first time! All are oil on wood panel in an Altoids tin, and will be available this evening on my website (link in bio) at 7:30pm MST.

Football fans watching the game at the bar! 🏈🍺 This is not a place you would typically find someone painting…

I painted this about 2 weeks ago at a sports bar in Nashville. Right around this same time, my account reached 400K followers. Thank you to all of you who have joined me on this journey of painting, and thanks to all of you who have stuck around.

I’ve been taking a break from posting, as is ordinary for me from time to time. I was in Nashville painting a mural, and there wasn’t much extra time to do these miniatures while I was there. Unfortunately this is the only mini I painted while I was there.

In other news, for those of you still reading this, I’m working on a book with a publisher, which should be available summer 2024.
Sometimes this kind of painting is like developing a photo print, where the development time is about an hour and 45 minutes and the exposure is fully manually created. 🍂

After viewing the annular solar eclipse two weeks ago, the thought occurred to me to do some kind of a painting of the event. Rather than painting the eclipse itself, I figured I would do a light and shadow study of all the little eclipse projections on the street. Each opening between leaves in the trees acts like a pinhole camera, projecting lots of images of the eclipse onto the ground. 🌙🌙🌙🌙🌙🌙🌙

Grisaille painting of the Flatirons in the rain. This was a fun challenge to paint all the subtle greys. A “grisaille” is a painting executed in shades of grey. This was painted with Titanium White and Torrit Grey.
By the way, Torrit Grey is an interesting paint. It is a collection of all of the pigments that get collected in the air filtration system in Gamblin’s paint factory. Every spring they make an oil paint from all that extra pigment,  which ends up being a neutral grey tone, and it’s slightly different every year. The tube I have was a promotional item from maybe 2011 or 2012 when (I think) they first started making it. I just found it in my supplies recently and decided to try it out. #grisaille #grisaillepainting #miniaturepainting #minipleinair

I hope all of you who traveled on one of these things for the holiday have a safe and smooth return flight home. ✈️

This one-of-a-kind mini oil painting in a mint tin is available now in my shop (link in bio). In case you missed the drop earlier this morning, there will be another one in about 2 1/2 hours at 5:30pm MST.

‘Chasing the light’ means changing your painting as the light changes.

Should you ever ‘chase the light’ as a plein air painter? Usually it’s not an good idea! However, this is a special case where what usually would have been a bad choice worked out absolutely fine, particularly because of the quick nature of the mini format.

DeVoto Memorial Cedar Grove is a protected grove of giant old-growth cedar trees in the inland temperate rainforest of Clearwater National Forest, Idaho. The closest city is Missoula, Montana, about an hour away.

If you are in Miami for @artbasel this week, stop by the mural I made with my buddies @jasontgraves and @raw.sol — we painted a mural of great white shark in the @wynwoodmuralfest for @oceanfirstinstitute. Check out JP’s work and give him a follow — his paintings are super interesting, as well as the rest of the artists represented by Poulsen (booth 104 on the Art Miami side). By the way, today is the last day to see shows at Art Basel in Miami.

Merry Christmas!

Here’s an unconventional painting to post on Christmas Day. Take this breadcrumb with a grain of salt: This is a painting of a daytime view of a similar craft to the “traveling star” that guided several wise men to see a new king of wisdom who was going to be born approximately 2000 years ago.

“The appearance of the extraterrestrials with their beamships (singing lights) had nothing to do with publicity, neither in Bethlehem nor in Nazareth or Egypt. It was merely a quite normal appearance without a shielding because there was no danger in relation to an attack from the side of the human beings of Earth. And the human beings at that time did not give much thought to such beamship phenomena (now called UFO phenomena) because they simply accepted such events as divine miracles.” — ‘Talmud Jmmanuel’, Chapter 2, p. 50 (English translation from FIGU Canada)

Some things just can’t be painted from life, including this beamship, from a photo by ‘Billy’ Eduard Albert Meier from June 14, 1975 (used with his permission).
⭐️ Winter in Boulder, Colorado ⭐️ Happy Holidays, everyone 😊

There’s a really great view of the mountains in Boulder from the top of the 14th & Walnut parking garage, above the RTD bus station. I’ve painted there several times. It’s a great place to watch the sunset, too!
Feelin’ Lucky?

Happy New Year! Here’s my top 9 for 2023.

I kinda feel like the whole “top 9” thing is so 5 years ago, but I’m feeling a little bit nostalgic right now because the year 2024 also feels a bit futuristic.

Look for some cool stuff coming from me this year, including lots more videos and… a BOOK!

- Remington

First mini plein air oil painting in an Altoids tin of 2024! It might be hard to tell, but I could barely hold on to this little metal box because it was absolutely freezing out once the sun went away. 🥶

🦈 This was a super fun mural to make with @raw.sol and @jasontgraves for the 2023 @wynwoodmuralfest in Miami last month. We worked with @oceanfirstinstitute to come up with the design of a purple and pink #greatwhiteshark which now resides on NW 24th St near NW 5th Ave. If you’re in the area, check it out and please take a photo in front of it, tag any one of us and maybe we’ll repost it in our story! 🦈

Random color palettes are so much fun! Here’s downtown Denver painted with Warm White, Mars Yellow, Imidazolone Brown and Radiant Green.

social_posts.post_text:
Morning light on the snow-capped peak of Mount Tronador — an extinct stratovolcano on the border of Argentina and Chile. 🇦🇷/🇨🇱

This was quite the flash of verve! A painting from a trip back in March of last year to Bariloche, a town in the northern Patagonia region of Argentina.

This is how this painting unfolded: I woke up just before sunrise and looked out the window to see if there would be any kind of sunrise. Immediately, I went from tired and groggy to fully alert — it was a completely clear day out, and Tronador was not only visible out my window, but it had apparently received a fresh dump of snow at some point in the last week while it was obscured by clouds. And if my judgement of the elements served me right, the pink sunlight of the sunrise would soon begin to touch the tippy top of the mountain. With that exciting thought in mind, I immediately exploded into action. With minutes to spare, I quickly applied fresh paint into a new tin, knowing that the light could begin to touch the mountain any second. This would be followed by 5-10 minutes, at best, of pink sunlight transitioning down the mountain.

In the moment before the sun hit the top of the mountain, I sketched the basic shape of my composition — a sort of elongated diamond shape — very basic and paintable in a short amount of time. And then, it happened: the top of the mountain suddenly looked as if it had been dipped in the most lovely and vibrant fluorescent pink sunlight. My goal was to record the mountain halfway lit by the first light of the pink sunrise, and now it was go-time. I blocked everything in in a matter of minutes. What I didn’t anticipate was how turquoise the snow would look at the base of the mountain as the pink light slowly cascaded down with the rising sun.

In the next 30 minutes or so, I worked from memory, then used a photo reference to fill in some shadow details. This is one instance where I feel like it’s perfectly reasonable and acceptable to paint details from a photo reference over top of a base layer of plein air painting.
